## Store Contracts

- Product/category reads allow optional JWT; management writes require JWT plus
  service-level permission checks.
- Product prices, order totals, wallet amounts, and reference incentives are cents.
- Products include `original_price`, `stock_unlimited`, `is_active`, and
  `special_actions` JSONB exposed as JSON string.
- Cart routes are authenticated; guest checkout sends explicit `items` in
  `/store/checkout` and does not rely on server cart state.
- Checkout supports `delivery_cash`, `wallet`, `card_{id}`, demo provider, and
  Stripe provider depending on configuration.
- Wallet routes expose balance, topups, transactions, and user-managed cards.
- Reference codes pay the code owner once per order through wallet credit; users
  cannot use their own active code.
- Special actions execute when an order is completed, and paid special-action
  orders can auto-complete after successful payment.
- Store catalog mutations broadcast `store:update`; cart and checkout outcomes
  push directly to the buyer.
- Store order mutations push `order:update` to buyers, store managers, and
  product owners; product owners also receive `store_order` notifications and
  system inbox messages with seller-scoped order details.
- Store order mutations also propagate `order:update` to the `order:{id}`
  resource subscription so open order detail/cards update across tabs in real
  time.
- DEFCON reset clears jail/history/counter pressure but must preserve trusted
  citizens; verified priority access should grant a short user bypass and promote
  the current IP to trusted.
- DEFCON telemetry classifies the adaptive allowance as `low`, `guarded`,
  `elevated`, `high`, or `critical`; clients use this server-owned threat level
  for status colors rather than duplicating limiter thresholds.
- Order item fulfillment is vendor-scoped: product owners may update only their
  own line items' `vendor_status`/`vendor_note`, stock reservation/release follows
  those lines only, and the parent order status is an aggregate such as
  `pending`, `vendor_review`, `accepted`, `rejected`, or `completed`.
- The product-owner selling role is named `Vendor`; legacy `store-seller` data
  should be migrated into it while preserving `store.product-seller` and
  `store.product-new` permissions.

## User Read Contracts

- `POST /api/users/batch` is a guest-safe bounded read for high-fanout rich-user
  UI. It accepts at most 50 unique positive IDs and returns the users found.
- The batch route reduces HTTP fan-out; individual profile routes remain the
  authoritative fresh-read path for full profile screens.

## Persistence Contracts

- PostgreSQL 16, per-tenant databases on shared instance.
- Pool defaults: open 100, idle 50, lifetime 30 minutes.
- Migration policy is in `.specs/migrations_spec`.
- Key tables include users/auth/session/RBAC, forum, products/cart/orders/payments,
  wallet/cards/reference payouts, inbox, notifications, site_config, pages,
  page comments, data sources, uploads/media history, analytics.

## Upload/SSR Contracts

- Uploads are user-isolated under `uploads/users/{userID}/{type}/`.
- Images: JPEG/PNG/WebP/GIF <= 10 MB with dimension validation.
- Videos: MP4/WebM/OGG/MOV <= 50 MB.
- Traversal (`..`) is rejected.
- `internal/ssr` rewrites SPA HTML with SEO/site config and serves sitemap data.

## Invariants

- Security-sensitive operations follow `.specs/security_architecture_spec`; route
  middleware and frontend checks never replace service-level policy enforcement.
- API JSON must go through `utils.WriteJSON` / `utils.WriteError`.
- Business logic and SQL must not live in handlers.
- Auth secrets must never be cached in public user models.
- Landing page is `site_config.landing_page_slug`; there is no `is_index`.
- WebSocket pushes are part of mutation correctness, not optional decoration.

